Melissa Kwan is a 3x bootstrapper. Here's what she said are the 11 most shocking surprises on her way to $1m ARR (everyone disagrees with #10 but I swear by it):

1. Everything they thought would make a huge impact, did not.

They got 1 customer from being top 3 on Product Hunt. 18 trials from a 250k person newsletter. Spent 7 months on a huge design update, zero lift.

2. Product-led is 10x harder than sales-led.

PLG is the hardest nut to crack. Getting someone to find you, sign up, try the product, then convert all on their own is HARD.

3. The market wasn't as ripe as they thought.

Given live webinars (her product) have been widely adopted, they thought automating them would be an easy sell. Turns out, it wasn't a concept most people could grasp without a demo.

4. Consumers are more discerning and less forgiving than ever.

Doesn't matter how great your product is and how many features you have, users will find the fringe case you can't solve and bounce.

5. The amount of time they spent on content creation.

LinkedIn, blogs, backlinks, templates, customer stories, podcasting, videos, guest posting, webpages, help articles, workshops, thought leadership.

6. A single user can cause scaling issues and uncover system flaws.

One user sent so many webinar attendees in 10 days into their system that it was 400x the average user. They never imagined a user like this could exist and was unprepared.

7. Plan limitations are for not losing money (not just making money).

Since they didn't have usage limits, they lost $8k in streaming costs due to the incident in #6. They had to put limits in to restrict similar power users.

8. Pricing strategy can be the difference between profit and loss.

They grandfathered existing customers when they increased prices against the advice of our peers. That could have been $30k/m to invest towards platform costs and hiring.

9. Incremental growth month over month amounts to meaningful revenue.

They grew 10-20% MoM in the 1st year, 5-10% MoM in the 2nd, 1-7% MoM in the 3rd. It often felt too slow and was discouraging, but they got there.

10. You don't need all the fancy metrics to know what to prioritize.

The only thing they obsessed over was the voice of customer through support tickets. Issues, requests, feedback and suggestions. Their roadmap was designed accordingly.

11. $83k/month is not a lot.

There always seemed to be another expense, another hire, another investment. They're capital efficient with outsourcing and contractors. CEO/CTO/COO make salary concessions, and they were still below break even.

